This paper deals with the problem of estimating spatial density functions from high-resolution satellite imagery using a neural network component. The paper proposes a novel approach that uses only coarse-grained density aggregates to train a pixel-level density estimator. This approach involves the use of neural networks and machine learning techniques, which are commonly associated with the computer vision (cs.CV), machine learning (cs.LG), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also deals with the problem of classifying buildings as residential or non-residential, which involves the use of graph-based methods (cs.GR) and natural language processing (cs.CL). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories for this paper are cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.GR, and cs.CL.
